<HL>
   Japan's Kaifu Sets Out for South Asia
   In Effort to Assure Link to the Region
   ----
   By Kathryn Graven
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3C
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Riding a wave of popular support at home, Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu sets out tomorrow for a nine-day tour
of South Asia to show Japan's commitment to Asia and to
helping developing economies.
   While the rest of Japan celebrates the annual Golden Week
of holidays, Mr. Kaifu will pay official visits to India,
Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Indonesia. It is the
first time in six years that a Japanese head of state has
visited the region.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Ministry officials say the purpose of his trip is
to reassure Japan's neighbors that despite all the recent
changes in Europe, Tokyo still places a high priority on
South Asian economic development. Officials say Mr. Kaifu
will stress that whatever Japanese aid and investment goes to
Europe it will not come at the expense of South Asia and the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN.
   Japan is already South Asia's biggest foreign aid donor,
handing over $1.1 billion in official development assistance
and loans to India, Bangladesh, Pakistan and Sri Lanka in
1988, up from about $970 million in 1987. Indonesia, the
single largest recipient of Japanese aid, received about $984
million in aid and loans in 1988, up from $707 million in
1987.
   But since there are no major burning political issues
between Japan and these countries at the moment, political
analysts say Mr. Kaifu is likely to use the diplomatic junket
to further bolster his domestic standing.
   "Increasingly, Japanese prime ministers have limited room
for action at home. So they rely on foreign policy to enhance
their domestic power," says Takashi Inoguchi, a professor of
political science at Tokyo University.
   Already, Mr. Kaifu appears to have grasped this tactic. In
his early days in office, he was seen as a puppet prime
minister, easily manipulated by former Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita. But since the Lower House elections in February,
Mr. Kaifu has won high marks for his delicate handling of
heated bilateral trade issues with the U.S. A recent poll by
the Yomiuri Shimbun showed his approval rating has risen to
56.1%, up from 52.9% in March and the highest since he was
inaugurated last August.
   At the same time, political analysts say Mr. Kaifu wants
to widen Japan's foreign policy field beyond ties to the U.S.
"He wants to show that he has contacts in Asia," says
Hiroichi Yamaguchi, a senior researcher at the Institute of
Developing Economies in Tokyo.
   While the timing of the trip takes advantage of the
holiday lull in Japan, observers say it also gives Mr. Kaifu
the chance to sound out South Asian leaders on their views on
global issues before the summit of advanced industrialized
nations in Houston this July. Increasingly, developing
countries in Asia are relying on Japan to voice their
concerns at international meetings.
   Analysts also expect that the governments of India,
Bangladesh, Pakistan and Sri Lanka will all ask the Japanese
government to encourage more private investment in their
countries. Currently, less than 1% of Japan's overseas
investment goes to South Asia.
   For all the expected toasts to improving relations, few
political analysts expect Japan to suddenly start playing a
more active role in the region's conflicts. Foreign Ministry
officials say Mr. Kaifu will encourage the governments of
India and Pakistan to continue their efforts towards peace,
but that Japan has no intention of playing a role as a
mediator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0135
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0135.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Guinness Engages in Spirited Campaign
   To Upgrade the Image of Scotch Whisky
   ----
   By Jonathan D. Silver
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   U.GUI
</CO>
<IN>
BEVERAGES (BVG)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Britain's Guinness PLC is pinning much of its
huge spirits division's future on a campaign uncorked last
year to revive the tarnished image of Scotch whisky.
   Upgrading the status of hard liquor in the eyes of
drinkers marks both the third and most crucial stage of a
revamping of the Guinness spirits unit, prompted by what the
company sees as a flight to quality among drinkers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's the longest and the toughest" stage "and the one
that will ultimately determine if we succeed," says Tony
Greener, managing director of the company's United Distillers
division.
   The image-polishing efforts by Guinness cut across all its
spirit brands, which include Gordon's and Tanqueray gins and
vodkas, Pimm's and IW Harper bourbon.
   But the focus is clearly on its flagship liquor, scotch,
and a handful of high-quality brands under which it is
marketed in different countries, among them White Horse,
Bells and Johnnie Walker.
   Scotch sales alone accounted for between 50% and 75% of
the company's #691 million ($1.13 billion) pretax profit
during the last fiscal year, analysts reckon, and many
forecast double-digit profit growth for scotch for the next
two years.
   Overall, the spirits division racked up #542 million in
pretax profit last year, up 23% from the #440 million
realized in 1988. Analysts expect the division to pull in
between #620 million and #645 million in 1990 against
companywide pretax profit of between #808 million and #843
million.
   Spirits mark the largest of a number of successes for
Guinness, which also owns big brewing operations, gourmet
food and wine, a publishing division and a 24% stake in the
French luxury goods group, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton
S.A.
   Shortly after crafting United Distillers in 1987 from a
string of acquisitions, the company set out on a three-point
strategy to resurrect the reputation of hard liquor in a
world that had been won over to beer, wine and soft drinks.
Guinness's first move was to remake its marketing
organization; this was followed by a clampdown on
distribution.
   In the past year, it has launched the last of the three
phases, aimed at polishing the image of its products. Armed
with an annual $250 million ad budget -- more than double
that of 1987 -- as well as a potent range of labels, Mr.
Greener says United Distillers hopes to win back respect for
spirits within five years.
   Guinness entered the spirits world with its 1985
acquisition of Arthur Bell for #360 million. It followed that
with its purchase of Distillers Co. in 1986 for #2.5 billion
and Schenley in 1987 for #480 million.
   Guinness paid dearly in penalties and bad publicity for
Distillers, a volume-driven group that flooded the market
with an enormous range of brands.
   In the wake of the acquisition, Guinness was found in
breach of takeover regulations in its handling of the hostile
bid and last year was forced to pay #85 million in
compensation to former Distillers shareholders. A number of
former Guinness executives and advisers are now on trial on
charges ranging from attempting to pervert the course of
justice to destroying and falsifying documents.
   United Distillers has surfaced from beneath the cloud of
the "Guinness Affair" sporting a vastly different structure.
   High volume had marked the late 1970s and early 1980s,
which saw a glut of scotch brands and a decline in demand. To
pull its spirits operations out of a potential bog, Guinness
hired Mr. Greener away from what is now Dunhill Holdings PLC
in 1987 to spearhead the revival. For Mr. Greener, credited
with switching Dunhill's focus from tobacco to luxury goods,
taking Guinness in a new direction was familiar work.
   Mr. Greener pulled the division through what he describes
as "12 months of quite a lot of grief" during which "we
completely changed the whole organizational structure of the
business."
   Mr. Greener sees an opportunity to re-establish the image
of its upscale liquor brands in the midst of a trend toward
more moderate intake in food and drink. Rather than volume,
he says, consumers are leaning toward an "appreciation of
good things."
   United Distillers culled the cheaper brands from its
product ranges. In the United Kingdom, for example, the
number of brands was slashed by about half. Similar moves
were made elsewhere.
   Some analysts say that the number of labels is still quite
a handful. But most point out that every country has its own
favorites, and United Distillers must offer a range of prices
for its quality products in each market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0134
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0134.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rival Paper's
   End Fails to Aid
   Pulitzer Stock
   ----
   By James P. Miller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PLTZ
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   ST. LOUIS -- Pulitzer Publishing Co.'s flagship St. Louis
Post-Dispatch paper has regained its monopoly as the city's
sole daily, following the failure of the upstart St. Louis
Sun.
   But the day after the late-afternoon announcement of the
Sun's fate, Pulitzer shares fell 25 cents to close at $27.25.
Analysts said the market's indifferent reaction reflected
just how little of a factor the Sun actually was, in
comparison to the ongoing softness in advertising sales that
is plaguing the Post-Dispatch, along with many other
newspapers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth F. Cook, an analyst with Burns, Pauli &amp; Co. in St.
Louis, said, "I think an awful lot of the Sun's demise was in
the stock already. There was an expectation that this thing
wasn't working, that it was only a matter of time" before
Ingersoll Newspapers Inc. folded the Sun. The Sun began
printing in September and lasted only seven months.
   In recent quarters, Pulitzer has conceded that the new
competition had helped push down Post-Dispatch earnings,
although the media concern has stressed that a weak
advertising market played a bigger role. Largely because of
the downturn at the Post-Dispatch, Pulitzer's earnings for
the first quarter tumbled 70% to $906,000, or nine cents a
share, from the year-earlier $3 million, or 29 cents.
   The Sun's "impact has been primarily on {Pulitzer's} cost
side" in terms of promotional and other efforts to counter
the new competitor, said Mr. Cook. He noted that the Sun
never hurt circulation at the Post-Dispatch, and said it's
unclear just how many ad dollars it had drawn from the
Post-Dispatch.
   At least for now, Mr. Cook said, he is holding to his
earlier projection that Pulitzer will have per-share earnings
of about $1.40 for the current year. In 1989, the company had
earnings of $31.4 million, or $3 a share, but the figures
were boosted by a net $12.7 million gain from sale of a
broadcasting property.
   A.G. Edwards analyst Michael Kupinski said, "Advertising
support for the Sun wasn't that significant." The Post's
recent earnings declines "have been 60% the result of the
economy, 40% the Sun," he said. Although "when you return to
a monopoly status, that's always good" because of the
increased leverage over advertising rates, he doubted there's
much near-term advantage to be gleaned from the death of the
Sun. "Looking forward," however, "it's a positive" for
Pulitzer, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0133
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0133.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   Financial Females Are Heard on the Street
   ----
   By Jewelle W. Bickford
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   The havoc visited on Wall Street since the 1987 stock
market crash has hit women even harder than men. Let into the
club in significant numbers only a decade ago, many now have
been laid off or shoved aside as Joanies-come-lately in the
frantic downsizing of a chastened but not chaste industry.
   So what's next? "Wall Street Women" (Knopf, 177 pages,
$19.95) by Anne Fisher, a former Fortune magazine reporter,
advertises on its jacket that the reader will be told how the
Street and women fared in the 1980s and where they are going
in 1990s. The book does better with the history than with the
speculation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As a chronicle of the turbulent past, "Wall Street Women"
is an often-compelling narrative, told through the voices of
top-ranking financial women. Interviewing female traders,
money managers, analysts and deal makers about their jobs,
the author finds these women as determined to succeed as
their male counterparts. They work just as well as men under
intense pressure and abnormally long hours.
   But they are different from the men around them. They are
less likely to value themselves mainly by their positions or
salaries. They seem to know that men find women scary who
make salaries in six or seven figures, and as a result Wall
Street women try to marry men making just as much money as
they do or who are in professions that aren't measured by
money: artists, writers, academics.
   They also are reluctant to spend the enormous incomes they
earn as freely as their male peers. Yes, many have the
obligatory second house in Connecticut or the Hamptons. But
most avoid the ostentation and conspicuous consumption
typical of their male counterparts. Indeed, ambivalence about
the unreal pay scales, slavish hours and recent market
turmoil are causing many to rethink their lives.
   All of this is told in an engaging style, without
bitterness, cynicism or, unfortunately, much that is new.
Throughout the four segments of the book (the work
environment, attitudes toward money, their background, and
finding a sense of balance), the reader is frustrated by Ms.
Fisher's seeming reluctance to probe.
   For example, C. Austin Fitts, the first female partner at
Dillon, Read &amp; Co., now commissioner of the Federal Housing
Administration in Washington, is shown describing her view of
how to get ahead: "If you're a `girl,' men hesitate to yell
at you if you do something stupid. And sometimes the only way
to learn is by getting yelled at. So I always sought out
people to work for who would yell at me. People that nobody
else wanted to work for, because they were known as
screamers. And I'm tough on the young women who work for me."
   But does she scream at them? And what do the women who
work for her make of hard-boiled Ms. Fitts? The author didn't
ask. Nor did she press Marilyn LaMarche, the first and only
female managing director at Lazard Freres &amp; Co., who followed
a kinder, gentler route to success: "You have to know how to
read and write well, and you have to know how to analyze a
financial statement. But more important than that: You must
have humility. You must have integrity. And you must work
hard."
   Fine. But why is there only one woman partner at Lazard
Freres? How hard did Ms. LaMarche have to lobby the guys to
get promoted? And is it only the women who were expected to
be humble in an industry known for its arrogance? I felt like
begging the author to at least ask the questions.
   And what of the future of women in this business?
   Ellen Lee's views of her work as an investment banker at
Ernst &amp; Co. suggest to me that now may be the time for us to
cling to what women have been traditionally taught. "Figuring
out what others need and want, and then bending over backward
to provide it, are skills traditionally inculcated and
encouraged in girls, not boys. Men are awful at it
generally," Ms. Lee notes. "The Street has a male dominated
personality. There's a lot of strategizing going on, but not
much real planning."
   The reader would like these thoughts put in a larger
context. Do other women agree? Is there a growing recognition
among men that women with traditional feminine skills are
needed as a part of a team approach to a client? Do those
skills work better in larger firms or smaller firms, where
every person must count? Indeed, is there any common ground
between the advocates of screaming and those reflecting a
more "feminine" approach? "Wall Street Women" offers few
answers.
   Although the book fails to probe where it should, it does
provide valuable anecdotal evidence of how a wide variety of
styles has worked and can continue to work for women in a
world that until a few years ago almost totally excluded us.
We're here, and despite the layoffs, despite the volatility
of the financial markets and the disintegration of
established firms, we're here to stay.
   ---
   Ms. Bickford is president of Trepp Financial Services Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
