<LP>
   SCHAUMBURG, Ill. -- Motorola Inc. said it will begin
constructing a $50 million assembly plant in Japan to produce
semiconductors for its customers in Asia.
   Responding to increasing demand from customers in Japan
and elsewhere in the Far East, the new plant will focus on
the assembly of both high-capacity memory devices, and
mid-range and high-end microcontroller chips that the company
said meets expanding market needs for surface-mount packages.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The plant will be owned and operated by Nippon Motorola
Ltd., a Tokyo subsidiary of Motorola, a maker of electronic
equipment and semiconductor chips.
