<HL>
   Thursday's Markets:
   Stocks Post
   Small Gain;
   Bonds Slip
   ---
   Broader Stock Indexes
   Display Weakness;
   Dollar Strengthens
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Stock prices rose modestly even as the ailing bond market
took another turn for the worse that pushed the yield on the
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond above 9%.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 10.14 points to
2676.58 in moderate trading. But broader market averages
didn't perform as well. Analysts also noted that more issues
on the New York Stock Exchange fell than rose, a signal that
investors remain unenthusiastic about stocks. The dollar
strengthened against most foreign currencies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tracked bond prices in early trading, rising
a bit as the long-bond price rose, then falling in tandem
with declining bonds. But as bond prices continued to sink
through much of the day, stocks reversed course and rose,
helped in part by some better-than-expected first-quarter
earnings reports.
   But analysts cautioned that with the yield on the
Treasury's benchmark issue now above the psychologically
important 9% level, stock prices almost certainly can't hold
at current levels. They said first-quarter earnings reports,
although in some instances surprisingly good, aren't nearly
strong enough overall to insulate stock prices from the
effects of rapidly rising interest rates.
   "This break above 9% is very serious," said Ken Spence,
director of the technical analysis group at Salomon Brothers.
"The stock market's response may lag a little bit, but some
event will set investors off."
   Mr. Spence said yesterday's price gains came largely from
computer-assisted program trading related to stock index
arbitrage. But he pointed out that for much of April, more
issues have fallen in daily trading than have risen. "That
says the broad market is much weaker than the Dow," he said.
   But even the bigger, well-known and more liquid blue-chip
stocks in the Dow average offer only temporary safety if
rates continue rising, and eventually will come under selling
pressure, he predicted.
   In any case, investors are looking to today's release of
the government's estimated first-quarter gross national
product as the potential event that could set off big moves
in both stock and bond prices. While economists are
predicting that first-quarter economic growth will come in at
about 2.7%, more than twice the fourth-quarter growth rate of
1.1%, some bond traders are worried that it will be even
higher. If that's the case, bond prices could tumble still
further, taking stock prices with them.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices climbed in modest trading. Volume on the New
York Stock Exchange totaled 141.3 million shares. But
declining issues on the Big Board were ahead of gainers 764
to 677.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar rose. In late New York trading the U.S.
currency was quoted at 1.6803 marks and 159.23 yen, compared
to 1.6785 marks and 158.75 yen Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0070
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0070.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Wang Labs to Post `Significant Loss';
   Data General Has Deficit for Quarter
   ----
   By William M. Bulkeley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   WANB DGN
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
EARNINGS (ERN)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Wang Laboratories Inc.'s revenue slump worsened in the
third quarter, ended March 31, and one-time charges caused a
"significant loss" for the quarter, Richard W. Miller,
chairman, president and chief executive officer, said.
   Mr. Miller said in an interview that by the end of June,
Wang expects to reduce employment to about 20,000, down from
22,000 now. About 1,500 of the reduction represents employees
at units that are being sold but the planned level is lower
than Wang had previously disclosed. A year ago, the Lowell,
Mass., concern had about 31,000 workers before it began
cutting.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Miller had previously warned that the third-quarter
operating loss would be worse than analysts expected. The
one-time charges are mostly related to the sales of certain
operations to raise cash and reduce debt.
   Separately, Data General Corp., Westboro, Mass., another
minicomputer maker attempting a turnaround, reported a net
loss of $8.6 million, or 29 cents a share, compared with net
income of $7 million, or 23 cents a share, for its fiscal
second quarter, ended March 31. Revenue fell 8.2% to $314.8
million from $342.7 million.
   The two companies' results emphasize that the computer
industry isn't enjoying any universal upturn, despite the
better-than-expected results reported by International
Business Machines Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp. last
week.
   Mr. Miller of Wang said that revenue for the quarter was
down more than the 13% decline recorded during the first half
of the fiscal year. In the year-ago third quarter, Wang
reported a restated net loss of $63.7 million, or 39 cents a
share, on revenue of $721.4 million. Mr. Miller declined to
be specific about earnings, which Wang expects to report
today.
   He said that the results reflect the weakness of the
midrange computer industry, especially in the U.S. He said
European markets were about flat and some Asian markets were
up but Australia was down.
   The sales slump was worst in January and February when a
reorganization of corporate marketers to focus on customer
segments such as banks, lawyers and insurance companies
caused a "loss of momentum," he said. He added that "for
March and so far in April, we feel better."
   Wang will take one-time charges related to the planned
sales of its international leasing business, its Intecom
subsidiary and a financial information services business,
which are expected to be completed in a few weeks. Wang
previously announced sales agreements but hasn't disclosed
the write-offs. Charges will cover reductions from book value
and certain tax contingencies related to the leasing
business.
   Following the sales, Wang will pay off bank debt, reducing
such debt to $65 million. That would be down from $575
million last summer when Wang faced the credit crunch that
led to Mr. Miller's being hired to succeed Frederick A. Wang,
son of the late founder and chairman, An Wang. In that period
Wang has arranged to sell $600 million of "non-strategic"
assets, and still plans to sell $200 million more, Mr. Miller
said.
   In addition to its bank debt, Wang has $450 million in
long-term debt at relatively low interest rates.
   Mr. Miller said that as a result of the cost cutting and
lower interest costs, Wang is "on a path that will come very
close to operating break-even" before interest costs for the
fourth quarter, ending June 30. In the year-ago fourth
quarter Wang reported a restated record net loss of $374.7
million, or $2.29 a share, on revenue of $741.3 million.
Previously, Mr. Miller had said that he hoped Wang would
return to profitability during the quarter.
   Data General's loss was "less than I'd been forecasting,"
said Jay P. Stevens, an analyst with Dean Witter. Data
General is changing from a company that makes proprietary
computer systems to one that makes industry-standard
computers that use the Unix operating system. However, its
proprietary business has been shrinking faster than the new
business grows.
   Ronald Skates, president and chief executive officer, said
that the second-quarter results were an improvement from the
first quarter and said "we expect that second-half results
will show an improvement over the first six months. We are
beginning to see evidence that the strategic steps we have
taken will allow us to grow and become profitable."
   Wang's Class B shares closed yesterday at $4.75, off 12.5
cents, in American Stock Exchange composite trading. Data
General closed at $9.50, up 50 cents, in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
