<HL>
   Business Brief -- Whirlpool Corp.:
   First-Quarter Net Fell 28%;
   Losses in Brazil Are Blamed
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WHR
</CO>
<IN>
HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Whirlpool Corp., hurt by deep losses in its Brazilian
interests, said first-quarter net income fell 28%, despite a
3.8% revenue increase.
   The Benton Harbor, Mich., maker of home appliances
reported net of $29.5 million, or 42 cents a share, down from
$40.7 million, or 59 cents a share, the year earlier. Revenue
rose to $1.64 billion from $1.58 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool said its "very strong earnings performance" in
the latest period was chilled by a 26-cents-a-share loss from
its equity interest in Brazilian operations; the year-ago
period had a loss of two cents a share from such operations.
   Brazil's economy has been brought to a "temporary
standstill" by recently introduced austerity measures there,
Whirlpool said, adding that there are modest signs of gradual
improvement.
   The company said North American revenue, operating profit
and unit volume rose, and added that it recorded a "solid"
first quarter in its European operations, which continue to
face tight margins.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday,
Whirlpool common closed at $21.375 a share, up 37.5 cents.
</TEXT>
