<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CITICORP'S DEBT RATING was cut by Standard &amp; Poor's, the
latest blow to the banking industry. The downgrading affects
$30 billion of long-term and short-term debt as well as
preferred securities, though commercial paper wasn't
affected. S&amp;P cited Citicorp's relatively low levels of
capital and loan-loss reserves, putting more pressure on the
bank to sell assets and issue more common stock.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Treasury bond and note yields surged above 9% to the
highest level in a year as dealers slashed prices to attract
buyers. One analyst called it a "fire sale." Stock prices
were mixed, while the dollar strengthened.
   ---
   Ames Department Stores filed for Chapter 11 protection,
ending efforts to become a giant discount retailer. The
filing came as talks with lenders stalled and many unpaid
vendors had stopped deliveries to Ames's stores. Ames was
hurt by its $800 million purchase of Zayre two years ago.
   ---
   New York Comex's president and chief executive, Arnold
Staloff, resigned after only nine months on the job. Staloff,
who was expected to rejuvenate the languishing exchange, is
said to have run into conflicts with Comex's trader
leadership.
   ---
   Donald Trump is discussing the sale or refinancing of
nearly every major asset he holds, including the recently
acquired Trump Shuttle.
   ---
   Robert Campeau has worked out a deal to regain control of
his troubled retail and real-estate empire. The Campeau Corp.
chairman agreed to repay his major personal creditor, which
would let him to recover Campeau shares seized in January.
   ---
   McDonnell Douglas plans to lay off about 3,000 workers at
its transport-aircraft unit, which posted an $84 million
first-quarter loss. The unit had been hoping to boost
employment for development of two new jetliners.
   ---
   OPEC plans to focus entirely on cutting production at next
week's meeting in order to prop up prices. The proposed 5%
reduction would apply only through May and June.
   ---
   A capital-gains tax cut would be considered by Ways and
Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski as part of a large
deficit-reduction package negotiated with the White House.
   ---
   Four major airlines posted dismal quarterly results,
mostly because of higher fuel costs. UAL and USAir each had
losses, while Delta and Southwest reported small profits.
   ---
   Xerox reported a bigger-than-expected loss of $254 million
for the first quarter, reflecting a one-time charge for its
financial-services unit. But the core business-equipment
operations posted a 20% profit gain.
   ---
   First Boston acquired 40% of Sealy in a restructuring of
an ill-fated $457 million bridge loan to the company.
   ---
   Wang's revenue slump worsened in the latest quarter, and
one-time charges will cause the computer company to post a
"significant loss," Chairman Richard Miller said.
   ---
   Chrysler is considering more ways to consolidate
production to cut costs. Possibilities include closing
another assembly plant in a few years in addition to the two
being shut this year.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 141,330,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2676.58, up 10.14; transportation 1139.05, up 2.67; utilities
206.61, up 0.31.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3214.67, off
14.81.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.11, up 0.74; spot
index 136.28, up 0.96.
   Dollar: 159.23 yen, up 0.48; 1.6803 marks, up 0.0018.
