<HL>
   Business Brief -- Volkswagen AG:
   Marketing Venture Formed
   With East German Partner
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7C
</SO>
<CO>
   G.VOW
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Volkswagen AG, a West German auto maker, said it formed a
50-50 marketing joint venture with its East German partner,
VEB IFA-Kombinat Personenkraftwagen.
   The venture, to be based in Karl-MarxStadt in East
Germany, will market the East German makes Trabants and
Barkas, and Volkswagen, Audi and SEAT vehicles. Individual
marketing operations will be set up for the different brands.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Volkswagen has said it expects its total auto
manufacturing joint-venture project with VEB IFA-Kombinat to
cost about five billion marks ($2.98 billion). In March, the
company said that it will invest an initial 350 million marks
and that it plans to assemble about 50 Volkswagen Polos daily
in a plant near Zwickau.
   Volkswagen said that 400 dealers in East Germany have
already been nominated for marketing of Volkswagen and Audi,
and 140 for marketing of SEAT. Through the dealer network,
Volkswagen said, its entire auto program, including the sale
of used cars, is to be made available.
</TEXT>
