<HL>
   Business Brief -- UAL Corp.:
   Wolf Tells Holders Meeting
   Unions' Offer Is `Doable'
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   UAL LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   The chairman of Chicago-based UAL Corp., Stephen M. Wolf,
told shareholders he believes a buy-out proposal from United
Airlines' three unions is a "doable transaction," after he
was pummeled with questions from holders skeptical of the
offer.
   Mr. Wolf was generally optimistic about the offer's
chances of success. At the same time, some of the statements
he made at UAL's annual meeting yesterday could hamper the
unions' efforts to obtain bank financing for the $4.36
billion bid.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Wolf, who the unions want to replace, criticized the
terms the bid offers to United's 26,000 non-unionized
employees. He also said he plans to announce a major aircraft
order shortly, a move that would place additional debt on the
airline at the same time the buy-out group is trying to
obtain financing.
   Mr. Wolf didn't say why he believes the unions' buy-out
proposal is unfair to non-unionized employees. The
concessions required under the unions' proposal are far less
than the concessions Mr. Wolf sought from the non-unionized
workers as part of an earlier labor-management bid. That bid
collapsed last fall when the buy-out group failed to obtain
financing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0019
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0019.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Citizens &amp; Southern Corp.:
   Earnings in First Quarter
   Fell 28% to $41.6 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   CTZ
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. reported that first-quarter
earnings fell 28% to $41.6 million, or 64 cents a share,
reflecting a $54.8 million charge for problem loans.
   The quarter's results, which compare with $57.8 million,
or 90 cents a share, posted the year before, were slightly
better than many analysts had expected.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last week, some analysts slashed profit estimates as much
as 50%, from a range of 93 cents to 97 cents a share,
following the Atlanta superregional's announcement that
results of a special examination by the U.S. Comptroller of
the Currency could force Citizens to take a first-quarter
charge to offset possible loan losses.
   The targeted exam is part of a current sweep by federal
regulators of commercial real-estate portfolios at big banks
in the Southeast. The exams, in most cases, have been
followed by charges to the companies' first-quarter earnings.
   Citizens' first-quarter addition brings its problem-loan
reserve to $248.9 million, a 15% increase from the $216.2
million set aside at year-end 1989. Loan write-offs decreased
31%, however, to $22.1 million from $31.9 million at
year-end.
</TEXT>
