<HL>
   Business Brief -- Norsk Hydro AS:
   Norsk Hydro Pretax Profit
   Fell 27% in First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7D
</SO>
<CO>
   NHY
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Norwegian industrial and energy concern Norsk Hydro AS
said pretax profit in the first-quarter tumbled 27% to 1.62
billion kroner ($249 million) from 2.23 billion kroner in the
first quarter a year earlier.
   Norway's largest company said its operating profit fell
26% to 1.89 billion kroner from 2.57 billion kroner in the
first three months of 1989, despite a 31% gain in oil and gas
operating profit to 797 million kroner from 608 million
kroner.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Per-share earnings were 4.00 kroner vs. 6.10 kroner in the
year-earlier period.
   Norsk said results were hurt by the agriculture, light
metals and petrochemicals divisions, which suffered from
prices lower than in 1989.
   The light metals division reported a 55% decline in
operating profit to 471 million kroner from 1.05 billion
kroner.
   Norsk announced plans to expand its Norwegian aluminum
production by 44% to 915,000 metric tons a year at a cost of
around 10 billion kroner.
   Hydro Aluminium AS produces 635,000 tons a year of the
light metal. Expansion plans concern smelters at Aardal Verk
and Sunndal Verk. Per-Christian Endsjoe, executive vice
president of the unit, said the first stage of the expansion
could be completed as early as 1993 or 1994.
</TEXT>
