<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Treasury Yields,
   At 9%, Reach
   12-Month High
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Susan Scherreik
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   C ADD JAPAN EUROP FRE
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Yields on Treasury notes and bonds spurted
above 9% yesterday, the highest level in a year, as bond
dealers slashed prices in an effort to attract buyers.
   "The market is really getting trashed; it's a fire sale,"
said F. Ward McCarthy Jr., a managing director at Stone &amp;
McCarthy Research Associates.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The high yields have encouraged scores of individual
investors to buy bonds for the first time in months. But
large institutional investors, who carry far more weight than
small investors, are reducing their bond portfolios for fear
that prices will continue to erode.
   Dealers said these big investors, both domestic and
foreign, began to sell bonds early in the day on rumors that
the government's report on first-quarter gross national
product, due out this morning, will show a large jump in
economic growth.
   While that may be good for businesses and the economy, the
bond market reacts badly to such news because investors fear
that a pickup in economic activity could lead to higher
inflation and interest rates, two trends that reduce the
value and appeal of most fixed-income securities.
   "With GNP coming, some investors are terrified. They don't
want to own bonds," said Jay Goldinger, a trader at Capital
Insight, a brokerage firm in Beverly Hills, Calif.
   The selling picked up steam as the Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond yield broke above 9%, a technical support level,
for the first time since May 1989. At that point, "the bond
market dropped like a stone," said Christopher Rupkey, a
financial economist at Mitsubishi Bank. "People were focusing
on 9% and when rates vaulted that level, selling
accelerated," he said. The yield rose as high as 9.04% but
ended at 9.03%.
   Michael Krauss, a technical analyst at Shearson Lehman
Government Securities Inc., believes the next technical
support level will be 9.10% which was the previous high yield
on the 30-year bond. He expects the bond market to rally at
that level, at least for a brief period. "I'm long-term
bearish," he said.
   Yesterday's selling caused the price of the benchmark
30-year Treasury bond to fall 3/4 point, a loss of about
$7.50 for a bond with a $1,000 face amount.
   Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Capital Markets Reports
expect the government to report this morning that
inflation-adjusted gross national product grew at an annual
rate of 2.7% in the first quarter. That's more than double
the 1.1% growth rate in the fourth-quarter and suggests to
traders that interest rates could be headed higher.
   "There is a general perspective that the market will lead
the Federal Reserve into a policy firming that eventually
will lead to a higher federal funds rate," said Joel Kazis,
manager of government trading at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co. The federal funds rate, which banks charge each other on
overnight loans, has remained at about 8 1/4% since late
December.
   Also contributing to the market's depression was a huge $1
billion offering of 30-year bonds by Chrysler Corp.'s Auburn
Hills Trust. Dealers said underwriters and some investors who
bought the bonds hedged their positions by selling 30-year
Treasury bonds. Chrysler's guaranteed exchangeable
certificates were priced at par to yield 12 3/8%.
   Adding to the market's bearish mood was concern about next
month's quarterly refunding of the federal debt, at which
time the government is scheduled to auction $30 billion of
securities.
   "If the market can't absorb $10.5 billion of two-year
notes," that were sold by the government on Wednesday,
"people are wondering what will happen," next month at the
refunding, said Mr. McCarthy. The two-year note auction was a
disappointment and caused bond prices to slide after the
auction results were announced. Although small investors were
big buyers of the two-year notes, institutional investors
shied away from the auction.
   The talk of the market was Chrysler's giant $1 billion
30-year bond offering.
   The size of the issue was increased from an originally
planned $800 million, a surprising development considering
underwriters at Salomon Brothers Inc. initially had trouble
drumming up sufficient demand for the bonds.
   But orders materialized after Salomon was forced by
investors to sweeten the terms of the issue. The 30-year
securities were priced at par to yield 12.375%, far higher
than the 11 3/4% to 12% yield that Chrysler anticipated.
Underwriters also made the bonds more attractive by adding a
noncall feature. The bonds had been slated to be callable in
10 years. Investors prefer noncallable issues because there's
no risk of early redemption if interest rates fall.
   The bond certificates will actually be issued by Auburn
Hills Trust, which will hold the title to Chrysler Technology
Center and lease the facilities back to Chrysler. The parent
company will guarantee the issue.
   Unlike previous Chrysler deals, yesterday's issue provided
bondholder protection in the form of event-risk language.
Essentially, should Chrysler debt be downgraded, or upgraded,
the coupon on the issue would be adjusted to reflect the
change.
   For example, if Moody's Investors Service Inc. or Standard
&amp; Poor's Corp. downgrade Chrysler debt one full rating
category, the coupon on the issue would be increased by 2.5
percentage points.
   In trading yesterday, most investment-grade bonds posted
declines of up to 3/8 point.
   Most junk bonds ended unchanged to slightly lower. One
notable exception: Ames Department Stores Inc. The retailer's
junk bonds, which had been losing ground for weeks, advanced
on news that the company filed for protection under Chapter
11 of the federal bankruptcy code.
   Ames's 13% senior subordinated reset notes rose two points
to close at 22. Sometimes, a company's bonds will rise
temporarily after a bankruptcy filing as so-called vulture
investors scramble to amass large blocks of bonds. The active
trading drives prices higher.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   The benchmark 30-year bond was quoted late at a price of
94 12/32 to yield 9.03% compared with 95 2/32 to yield 8.97%
on Wednesday. The latest 10-year notes ended at a price of 96
10/32 to yield 9.05% compared with 96 25/32 to yield 8.98% on
Wednesday.
   Short-term rates rose yesterday. The discount rate on
three-month Treasury bills ended at 7.83% for a bond
equivalent yield of 8.078% while the discount rate on
six-month bills ended at 8.01% for a bond-equivalent yield of
8.442%.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Issues
                                                                                                       

   Municipal bonds were unchanged to 3/4 point lower in late
dealings, as a large number of institutional sellers
contributed to the session's brisk activity.
   "There are more sellers than buyers," said one trader.
"We're very low and there are very few people sticking up
their heads to buy bonds."
   To characterize the market's weakening tone, a trader
pointed to the 2024 term bond of an issue of $283 million
Transmission Agency of Northern California revenue bonds.
Late in the session, the bond was quoted at 94 3/8 to yield
7.45%, which is eight basis points higher than the original
offering level. A basis point is a hundredth of a percentage
point.
   In new-issue activity, a Bear Stearns &amp; Co. group
successfully bid for $120 million East Bay Municipal Utility
District, Calif., water system subordinated revenue bonds.
The bonds were priced for reoffering to yield from 7.20% in
2001 to 7.60% in 2020.
   Among active bonds, the New Jersey Turnpike Authority's
7.20% issue due in 2018 fell 1/4 point to 95 1/4, to yield
7.60%.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   A rebound in the value of the yen and rumors that a large
Japanese securities firm was marking up prices boosted the
Japanese government bond market.
   Dealers said that trading activity, however, remained
thin. On Tuesday, the Finance Ministry auctioned the May
issue of the 10-year Japanese government bond. Market
participants said the top bidders at the auction were Salomon
Brothers Asia Ltd., Daiwa Securities Co., Yamaichi Securities
Co. and Nomura Securities Co.
   Dealers said with three of next week's trading sessions
closed for Japanese national holidays, the market is not
expected to move much by the end of the week.
   At the 3 p.m. JST (2 a.m. EDT) close of the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, the yield on the benchmark 10-year bond had risen
0.22 point to 86.11 for a yield of 7.345%.
   In other markets:
   -- British government bonds fell again, although the pace
of the declines slowed markedly after Wednesday's hectic
sell-off. Dealers said that yesterday's price declines were a
carry-over from Wednesday, when a wider-than-expected March
current account deficit caused long-term government bonds to
fall 1 3/8 point.
   Yesterday, the benchmark 11 3/4% Treasury bond due
2003/2007 ended 10/32 lower at 94 17/32 to yield 12.52%.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage rates are heading toward 11% because of recent
losses in the mortgage-securities market.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. offered yesterday to
buy fixed-rate 30-year loans from lenders for 10.67%, up
nearly one-tenth of a percentage point from Wednesday and the
highest rate in nearly a year.
   Since consumers pay about 3/8 percentage point more than
the Freddie Mac posted rate, fixed-rate mortgage soon should
be nearing 11%.
   Meanwhile, mortgage securities continued their recent
slide and ended 7/32 to 11/32 lower on the day.
   Government National Mortgage Association 9% securities for
May delivery ended at 93 10/32, down 10/32; the 9 1/2% issue
at 95 30/32, down 9/32; and the 10% issue at 98 19/32, down
7/32. Freddie Mac's 9 1/2% securities were at 95 3/4, down
11/32.
   Dealers said there was fairly heavy selling of mortgage
issues by a number of institutional investors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Demand for Industrial Materials Climbs
   ---
   Trend Indicates Manufacturing
   Is Exceeding Forecasts
   ----
   By Ralph E. Winter
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   RBW GR TKR WTHG DOW
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Rising demand for industrial materials signals a stronger
manufacturing pace than some people expected.
   U.S. manufacturing hit a recent bottom in January, when a
majority of the nation's auto plants closed for several weeks
to reduce inventories, and many other factories also
throttled back. Now manufacturing executives say business is
coming back surprisingly briskly, although it will be some
months before the order upturn bolsters profits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Business is picking up across the board," says Joseph H.
Stegmeyer, vice president and chief financial officer at
Worthington Industries Inc., Columbus, Ohio. "Orders are
strong at all nine locations across the country where we
process and distribute steel." In Columbus, Worthington's
plants are operating six or seven days a week to keep up.
   The upturn has boosted operating rates at the nation's
steel mills to nearly 90% of capacity, from 78% during
January. And it isn't only steel. Demand has improved for a
wide range of other industrial products as well, ranging from
castings to computer chips.
   Dow Chemical Co., Midland, Mich., reports strong demand
for its polyethylene and polystyrene plastics, as well as for
caustic and other basic chemicals. Nuts and bolts, truck
tires, anti-friction bearings and other manufactured items
used primarily by industry are doing much better, too.
   "I'm really pretty bullish," says Michael K. Evans, a
Washington, D.C., economic consultant. "Industrial production
will rise at a 4% annual rate for the balance of the year,"
he forecasts, bolstered by strong exports and higher business
spending for facilities and equipment. By contrast,
industrial production rose only 1% over the past 12 months.
   To be sure, Mr. Evans is more optimistic than most. Some
economists worry that we're seeing mainly an auto-related
uptick rather than a basic change. Factory jobs declined by
69,000 in the first quarter, says Maury Harris, chief
economist for PaineWebber Inc.
   "It's too early to say manufacturing has turned the
corner." He expects industrial output to edge up at only a 1%
to 2% annual rate for the rest of the year, because he
foresees little, if any, further recovery in auto production
and "weak demand for anything related to construction" or
home sales.
   While the National Association of Purchasing Management's
manufacturing index -- which includes orders, production,
inventories and other factors -- rose in March to the highest
level since last June, it remained below the point that would
indicate manufacturing was expanding.
   Furthermore, many manufacturers are reporting sharply
lower first-quarter profits, partly because prices of many
industrial products remain well below year-ago levels.
Despite another round of employment cuts and other
cost-reduction measures, earnings for all of 1990 are likely
to fall, many economists say, the second consecutive year of
decline.
   Buoyant demand in 1987, 1988 and early 1989 encouraged
producers to launch plant expansions and buy equipment to
relieve production bottlenecks. Some of that new capacity in
paper, plastics and other materials is coming into production
this year, holding down prices in spite of improving demand.
Meanwhile, wages, salaries and employee benefits are about 5%
higher this year.
   Increased international competition also limits the
ability of manufacturers to pass along cost increases,
"eroding corporate profits," says Theodore H. Tung, senior
vice president and economist for National City Bank of
Cleveland. "This isn't like the 1970s when U.S. companies
could charge whatever they wanted when demand picked up."
   Still, there's been a noticeable improvement in
manufacturing, partly reflecting the rebound in auto
production. Auto assemblies in the first quarter plunged to
less than 1.5 million, 23% below a year earlier, slashing
orders for steel, tires, glass and a host of other industrial
products. For the second quarter, however, auto makers expect
to turn out nearly 1.8 million cars, down a more modest 8.2%
from a year ago. Truck output will be almost flat with the
1989 second quarter and 21% above the first three months,
according to industry sources.
   While auto sales aren't booming, auto makers are keeping a
sharp eye on inventories, and nobody expects widespread plant
closings such as occurred last January. And auto makers won't
suddenly turn off the order faucet in a massive inventory
correction.
   Wagner Castings, a Decatur, Ill., automotive foundry, has
bounced back to near-capacity operation, after dropping to
about 50% from December through March. However, "we don't
know how much of current output is going to refill the
pipelines," says Ross D. Lake, executive vice president and
chief operating officer of Sudbury, Inc., Wagner's parent.
   But the manufacturing recovery goes well beyond the auto
industry. Non autodependent businesses such as plastic
resins, electronic parts and oil field equipment are showing
improvement, producers say.
   At Worthington, "our Chicago plant's orders are up very
strongly, and they don't do a lot of auto business," says Mr.
Stegmeyer. "Our South Carolina plant, which sells large
amounts of steel to producers of lawn and garden and
electrical equipment, also is up strongly." Overall,
Worthington's March orders were higher than the year
earlier's healthy levels, he says.
   For Timken Co.'s roller bearings, the auto market, while
improving, is one of the weaker spots, says Joseph S. Toot
Jr., president of the Canton, Ohio, bearings and specialty
steels concern. But because many other industries have picked
up, "we're enjoying a higher level of business than we
anticipated."
   Akron, Ohio-based B.F. Goodrich Co. has sold out
practically its full polyvinyl chloride capacity for the next
few months, says Don Knechtges, vice president, marketing and
business management, for the vinyl division. Demand has been
better than anticipated, putting the vinyl division "into a
pretty snug position." PVC is a basic plastic material used
for pipe, siding, wire insulation and a host of other
applications.
   As one indication of the PVC turnabout, Goodrich in the
past few weeks was able to put through a price increase of
three cents a pound, or nearly 10%, and plans another
two-cent rise for May. However, that would recover only about
half the price drop that occurred in the previous nine
months.
   Materials producers say they're confident customers are
buying for immediate use rather than to build inventory. "We
have many orders with very short lead times -- they need the
material now," says Worthington's Mr. Stegmeyer.
   In fact, the order upturn in part reflects the end of
inventory cutting. Companies started building stocks and
placing multiple orders for materials in late 1988 or early
1989, when prices were soaring and shortages appeared to be
developing. But they quickly cut orders in the 1989 second
half, when the economic slowdown turned those hedge buys into
excess inventory.
   Now stocks have returned to relatively low levels. The
Commerce Department reported last week that business
inventories in February shrank to 1.48 months' shipments,
from 1.51 months in January and 1.49 months a year earlier.
   Some manufacturers may have cut too deeply. RB&amp;W Corp., a
Mentor, Ohio, fastener manufacturer, is working overtime at
some plants to meet urgent delivery requests, says John J.
Lohrman, chairman and chief executive officer. Only six weeks
ago RB&amp;W was working 32-hour weeks, because customers weren't
ordering nuts and bolts. "Some of our customers apparently
overdid" the inventory cutting, and are asking for
accelerated deliveries now, he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900427-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900427-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Stocks End Higher on Earnings;
   Compaq Computer Up 4 1/4 to 98 1/4
   ----
   By Craig Torres and David Wilson
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Thanks to some surprisingly good earnings
reports, stocks finished higher for the second straight day
despite another slump in the bond market.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 10.14 to 2676.58.
The advance lacked broad participation: 764 issues declined
on the New York Stock Exchange while 677 advanced. Broader
market indices also gained, but not as much: Standard &amp;
Poor's 500-Stock Index rose 0.89 to 332.92; the New York
Stock Exchange Composite Index rose 0.36 to 182.66; and the
Dow Jones Equity Market Index gained 0.60 to 310.12. Volume
on the Big Board totaled 141,330,000 shares.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Treasury bond yields rose through the 9% level at
midmorning to 9.03% late in the day, a move that dragged down
stock prices. But stocks rebounded in afternoon trading, as
investors began buying stocks of large companies that have
reported strong earnings in recent days.
   "Even companies where earnings were down year over year
are reporting earnings that are higher than the consensus,"
said Joseph J. McAlinden, head of research at Dillon Read.
"And a broad cross-section of companies are coming in with
higher-than-expected earnings."
   One was Compaq Computer, which reported first-quarter
earnings of $2.13 a share, sharply ahead of most forecasts.
Earlier this week, investors shunned the stock, fearing bad
news. But yesterday Compaq shares recovered with an explosive
opening gain of 6. The stock finished 4 1/4 higher at 98 1/4
on 1.4 million shares.
   Today's report on first-quarter gross national product may
confirm the aggregate strength in the economy that seems to
be showing up in the earnings of many companies. A consensus
of estimates by economists polled by Dow Jones Capital
Markets report forecasts GNP growth at an annual rate of
2.7%. In the fourth quarter of last year, GNP rose at a 1.1%
rate. Additionally, two inflation measures based on GNP are
expected to have climbed at rates of more than 5% in the
quarter, well above fourth-quarter levels.
   Mr. McAlinden said the stock market's resilience in the
face of rising bond yields "is telling you that the American
business cycle is pretty decent."
   Said Thomas R. Walsh, head of equity trading at Nikko
Securities International: "On balance, I've seen people ready
to buy stocks now, which I haven't seen in a long time."
   Among other shares of large companies that are attracting
investors because of their earnings performance,
Bristol-Myers Squibb gained 2 1/8 to 54 7/8 on volume of 2.1
million shares. Prudential-Bache Securities increased its
1991 and 1992 earnings estimates and repeated a buy
recommendation on the stock.
   Du Pont, which rose 7/8 Wednesday after its first-quarter
earnings report met expectations, added another 1 1/8 to 37
on 1.7 million shares. First Boston raised the stock's
investment rating to "strong buy" from "buy" and increased
its estimate of 1990 earnings. The firm took the same action
on Dow Chemical, whose shares gained 7/8 to 62 1/4.
   Procter &amp; Gamble, which gained 1 1/8 Wednesday in response
to a well-received earnings report for its fiscal third
quarter ended last month, advanced another 1 1/4 yesterday to
70 3/4.
   Sara Lee went down 7/8 to 28 5/8 on 1.8 million shares
after Merrill Lynch trimmed its earnings projections for
fiscal 1990 and 1991 in the wake of Sara Lee's fiscal
third-quarter earnings report, issued Wednesday. The firm now
expects Sara Lee to report net income of $1.92 a share for
the year ending in June, down from a forecast of $1.95, and
$2.15 to $2.20 a share for the next year, down from $2.20 to
$2.25.
   Steven A. Kroll, president of SLH Asset Management, said
the recent rise in rates and numerous disappointments in the
first-quarter results released so far have made "proven
earnings growers" look more attractive.
   "Earnings, earnings and earnings -- that's the key," Mr.
Kroll said, adding that any rallies in the market at this
point "are going to be suspect" while the bond market
struggles and rates remain high.
   Safeway closed 10% above the price at which underwriters
sold a 10% stake in the company in an initial public
offering. Ten million shares were sold in the offering at
$11.25 each; the supermarket company's stock ended the
session at 12 3/8, with 2.2 million changing hands.
   Norton, which slid 1/2 to 88 1/4, was the most active Big
Board issue for the second consecutive session as 2.6 million
shares were traded. BTR of Britain, whose takeover offer of
$75 a share for the company was rejected, disclosed that it
had sold its entire 1.7% stake. As reported, Norton accepted
a $90-a-share bid from France's Saint-Gobain.
   Republic New York dipped 1/8 to 43 3/8 on 1.2 million
shares following the sale of about four million shares at
$43.50 apiece, made in connection with the company's
acquisition of Manhattan Savings Bank.
   Illinois Power fell 1 7/8 to 16. A hearing examiner with
the Illinois Commerce Commission recommended that the utility
receive a rate increase of $27.7 million, rather than the
$215.7 million increase it requested.
   Seagull Energy rose 1 to 22 5/8. The company reported that
first-quarter earnings rose about 23% from a year earlier and
the full-year outlook is "very positive."
   Conversely, Gleason tumbled 2 3/8 to 18 3/4 after posting
first-quarter net from continuing operations of 10 cents a
share, compared with a loss from continuing operations a year
earlier.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 0.23
to 344.75. Volume totaled 15,030,000 shares compared with
16,060,000 Wednesday. There were 266 issues advancing, 271
declining and 245 unchanged.
   Weatherford International gained 3/8 to 5 7/8 after the
completion of an offering of three million shares, sold at
$5.50 each.
</TEXT>
